abstract: May one interject a gentle protest against the use of the phrase "Christian name" in this connection? The Romans said praenomen, the French say prenom, and we have used the word "forename" for the last 365 years. It is as incorrect to speak of the Christian name of a Jew, for example, as it would be hopeless to expect a Christmas card from a Jewish rabbi.

abstract: NEWARK, N.J., Oct. 1. -- Joseph M. Sherlock of Troop D, Sixth United States Cavalry, died at his home, 38 Wright Street, last night of typhoid pneumonia. Sherlock was born in this city twenty-five years ago, and was engaged in the insurance business when he enlisted last June. He went with his regiment South, but as soon as the troops returned to Montauk he was stricken with malarial fever, which soon developed into typhoid.

abstract: PATERSON, N.J., Oct. 1. -- Thomas Hardy and Daniel McKelvey, two employes of the Laflin  Rand Powder Company, at its works at Mountain View, were killed to-day by an explosion. They were practically roasted alive where they stood. Hardy and McKelvey were expert grinders and had charge of the machinery in the "corning" mill, where the powder is reduced into grains. Hardy lived in Mountain View and McKelvey in Lincoln Park. Both leave families.

abstract: SAVANNAH, Ga., Oct. 2. -- For fifteen hours, from 3 o'clock this morning until 6 o'clock to-night, Savannah has been in the grasp of a West Indian storm. During that time the wind blew steadily from fifty to seventy miles an hour. While the city escaped with comparatively little damage, the loss of property among the sea islands of the Georgia and South Carolina coasts is believed to be heavy.

They were committed in default of bail. Armand Schmoll, managing Director of the Woodside Calf Manufacturing Company, made the complaints. He alleges the acts which led to the arrests were committed in February and from May to November of last year.

abstract: SANTIAGO DE CUBA, Oct. 14. -- Heavy rains during the last ten days have caused much sickness, especially among the members of the Signal Service. Out of fifty-three men, only seventeen are available for duty. The death rate at Santiago, however, continues very low. Persons who have lived here all their lives are unable to understand this low death rate, averaging for October up to date, only ten a day.

abstract: CHARLESTON, Oct. 14. -- Typhoid and malaria among the enlisted men stationed at Sullivan's Island is causing the commandant, Col. Rawles, much concern. At present 400 men are confined to quarters. abstract: To the student of sculpture this great series of reliefs has come like a revelation. It was not supposed that Roman art was capable of producing a work of such breadth of conception, of such an artistic combination of beauty and strength. abstract: LONDON, Oct. 19. -- Anthony Hope's new play, "When a Man's in Love," produced at the Court Theatre to-night, was cordially received. abstract: WASHINGTON, Oct. 21. -- The Director of the Mint in his report upon the production of the precious metals during the calendar year 1867, just submitted to the Secretary of the Treasury, states that the value of the gold produced in the United States during the period mentioned was $57,363,000. abstract: INDIANAPOLIS, Ind., Oct. 21. -- The President was in the city for two hours today. His visit to Indianapolis brought to the city an immense crowd of strangers, and all of the city itself turned out to give him welcome. Public schools suspended for the forenoon.
